<script type="application/ld+json">{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much should a church spend on ads?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most churches can start seeing real results with as little as $5-10 per day on Facebook ads. The O2F Method by RK Castillo recommends starting with a modest budget, testing what works, and scaling from there. A church of any size can begin with $150-300 per month and adjust based on the cost per visitor and engagement results."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are Facebook ads or Google ads better for churches?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Facebook and Instagram ads tend to perform better for churches because they allow you to reach people who aren't actively searching for a church but are open to an invitation. Google ads work well for people already searching for a church near me. A combined approach is ideal, but if you can only choose one, Facebook ads typically deliver more visitors per dollar for most churches."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What kind of content works best in church ads?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Testimonial videos, sermon clips addressing real-life struggles, and invitation-style ads that speak to felt needs consistently outperform generic church promotional content. The key is leading with the transformation someone can experience rather than promoting your church programs or building."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I measure if my church ads are working?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Track three key metrics: cost per click, cost per lead (someone who fills out a form or engages), and cost per visitor (someone who actually shows up). The most important number is how many new people walk through your doors on Sunday as a direct result of seeing your ad. Use landing pages, connection cards, and first-time visitor surveys to track this."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can small churches afford to run ads?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely. Small churches often see the biggest return on ad spend because they can offer a personal, welcoming experience that larger churches sometimes struggle with. With the right targeting and messaging, even $5 per day can generate meaningful results for a small congregation."
      }
    }
  ]
}</script>

